Test Plan for Login & Search Functionality (Updated)
Objective
To validate the login and search functionality of the ananas.rs platform using a production‑grade automation framework.
The objective is to ensure that all critical user journeys work correctly, edge cases are handled, security vulnerabilities are mitigated, and the UI is responsive – while maintaining a robust CI/CD pipeline.

Scope
Login functionality – valid/invalid credentials, empty fields, password boundaries, SQL injection, XSS, forgot password link, account lockout (expected but missing), responsive design.

Search functionality – valid, empty, and invalid search queries.

Cross‑browser compatibility – Chrome, Firefox, Edge (via WebDriverManager).

Responsive design – mobile (iPhone X) and tablet (iPad Pro) viewports.

CI/CD integration – GitHub Actions (automated on every push) and Jenkins pipeline (optional).

Containerisation – Docker support for isolated, reproducible test runs.

Types of Testing
Type	Description
Functional Testing	Valid login with correct credentials, error messages for invalid inputs, search with valid/invalid terms, forgot password link.
Security Testing	SQL injection, XSS attacks, special characters in email fields.
Responsive Design Testing	Login form display and functionality on mobile and tablet resolutions.
Cross‑browser Testing	Chrome, Firefox, Edge (local runs).
CI/CD & Container Testing	Headless execution in GitHub Actions and Docker, artifact generation (reports, screenshots, logs).
Negative & Boundary Testing	Empty fields, password length boundaries (min 8 chars, max 300 chars – known app bug).
Expected Errors / Edge Cases
Empty username and password fields.

Invalid email format (missing @, missing dot, special characters).

Incorrect password for a valid email.

Incorrect email with valid password.

Overly long password (300 characters – app returns generic error, not specific).

SQL injection attempts in username field.

XSS injection attempts.

Account lockout after 5 failed attempts (not implemented – test disabled).

