Key Framework Features
Page Object Model (POM) – maintainable, reusable page classes.

Data Providers – reduce code duplication for similar test scenarios.

Soft Assertions – collect multiple failures in a single test.

Retry Analyzer – automatic retry of flaky tests (up to 2 times).

Headless Mode – automatically enabled in CI/Docker environments.

Parallel Execution – TestNG XML for cross‑browser parallel runs.

Log4j2 – console and file logging with different levels (info, warn, debug).

ExtentReports – HTML reports with screenshots on failure.

Execution & Reporting
Local Execution
bash
mvn clean test                     # Chrome (default)
mvn clean test -Dbrowser=firefox   # Firefox
mvn clean test -Dtest=LoginTest    # Run only LoginTest
CI Execution (GitHub Actions)
Triggered on every push to main branch.

Runs on Ubuntu latest with headless Chrome.

Generates and uploads ExtentReport, screenshots, and logs as artifacts.

Docker Execution
bash
docker build -t ananas-tests .
docker run --rm -v "$(pwd)/extent-reports:/app/extent-reports" ananas-tests
Reports
HTML report: extent-reports/extent-report.html

Screenshots: screenshots/ (only on failures)

Logs: logs/automation.log

Known Limitations & Future Improvements
Application bugs – two tests disabled until the application implements lockout and password length validation.

CI headless issues – login redirect and search input are not reliable in GitHub Actions; affected tests are skipped in CI but pass locally.

Potential improvement – Use undetected-chromedriver or a real browser cloud service (SauceLabs, BrowserStack) for CI.